observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Supply Officer to do the following:

Initiate the requisition of supplies and inventories to be carried in stock in accordance with COA Circular No. 2002-003;

Prepare and maintain RIS, ICS, SSMI, and Property Issue Slip for issuance of supplies and inventories, whichever is appropriate;

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the heads of office concerned to observe the prescribed procedures in the requisition of supplies and inventories provided under COA Circular Nos. 2002-003 and 92-386.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:
Issue an executive order or internal memorandum identifying and requiring key employees or department heads to submit a timeline in adopting the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, within 30 days from issuance of such order or memorandum;
Require the municipal accountant and the GSO to maintain separate ledger and property cards and PAR or acquisitions of PPE and conduct regular reconciliation pending the cleansing of the PPE account;
Create an inventory committee that is responsible for the actual count of all PPEs owned by the LGU; and
To expedite the physical inventory taking, issue an internal memorandum requiring each employee to submit every semester a list of LGU properties under their custody, and let this be a requirement before the payment if any enhancement or productivity bonus.

We hereby reiterate the prior year’s audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:
Cease from granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance given to an accountable officer is initially settled or proper accounting thereof is made, and withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until settlement of their respective cash advances;
Send demand letters quarterly and instruct all accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances to liquidate their cash advances within 15 days from receipt hereof, or else refund the full amount advanced, otherwise, administrative and criminal prosecution may be sought by management and/or the audit team;
In the case of the deceased or those who have been separated from service, make representations with the proper prosecuting agencies of the government towards the institution of the necessary proceedings for the recovery of the amount of the cash advance as provided in Section 4.1 of COA Circular No. 86-256; and
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-08 dated August 17, 2023.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

reconcile the balances of sources of fund between the Utilization Report and accounting records and reports;

submit a correct Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM Fund for CY 2023.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant and/or other officer and employees concerned to:

submit the necessary Memorandum of Agreement for the Livelihood Assistance;

prepare and submit the necessary liquidation report on the utilization of fund for Livelihood Assistance, and Construction of the National Child Development Center;

immediately implement the identified project funded by the Department of Social Welfare and Development, if possible, or return the fund;

Follow-up with the Department of Agriculture the release of the 10% intended for Erenas Small Water Impounding Project (SWIP), and immediately prepare the appropriate liquidation of the fund; and

exert efforts to determine the details of the unreconciled amount of P115,201.34, and prepare the necessary accounting journal entries therefor.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant ensure that disbursements for infrastructure projects be supported with the following:

•	Certified copy of the page of the approved Annual Procurement Plan (APP) or Supplemental APP where the particular Infrastructure Projects subject of payment is indicated;

•	Contract or Purchase Order stamped "Received" by COA;

•	Irrevocable Standby Letter of Credit/Security Bond/Bank Guarantee;

•	Statement of Time Elapsed;

•	Certification from the end-user that the project is completed, inspected and accepted.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant submit bidding documents, contracts and all documents forming part thereof, in accordance with relevant rules and regulations.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

The City Accountant closely coordinate with the OIC – City Agriculturist and City Veterinarian regarding the breeding stocks of the City under their custody and reconcile the accounting records with their inventory reports;

The OIC – City Agriculturist and City Veterinarian provide the prevailing market price for each item of breeding stocks as basis of the City Accountant in taking up adjustments in the books to record the fair values of breeding stocks pursuant to Section 4.5 of COA Circular No. 2016-004 dated September 30, 2016 to present a correct and reliable balance of Breeding Stocks account in the financial statements;

The CSWDO must explain/justify in writing why the Chicken Layer project, with a project cost of Ᵽ471,555.00 and taken up as biological assets in the books of the City, was not reported immediately considering the period since it stopped   in CY 2018. Further, the City Accountant must assess or evaluate the Inventory Report submitted by the CSWDO to determine the extent of accountability over the project;

The City Accountant take up adjusting entries in the books relative to the BAs not recorded or those which were incorrectly taken up as Expense; and

The OIC – City Agriculturist and City Veterinarian ensure to promptly submit the updated inventory reports so that the City Accountant could immediately take up necessary adjustments in the books, if there are any.

We recommend that management consider in the guidelines of the Livelihood Assistance Program, the following requirements of essential documentation and information, and procedures relevant to the screening of beneficiaries to protect the interest of the government, to wit:

provision on the income level of the applicant to be granted the loan;

submission of a project proposal/ feasibility study duly supported with the projected income within the loan paying period or the financial reports for the years it is projected to be in operation;

assessment by an Evaluation Committee who will study and evaluate the applicant’s proposal and eligibility, and recommend its approval or disapproval to the City Mayor;

provision for the training and technical assistance by the LGU to the grantee;

provision for limitations on grants to applicants who still have unpaid balances of loans previously granted by the city; and

inclusion in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA), Item No. 8 in the guidelines which states that “Xxx. The loaner shall submit report on Return of Investment, six (6) months after the release of the loan.”

