We recommended that management:
Cease from granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance given to an accountable officer is initially settled or proper accounting thereof is made, and withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until settlement of their respective cash advances;
Send demand letters and instruct all accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances to liquidate their cash advances within 15 days from receipt hereof, or else refund the full amount advanced, otherwise, administrative and criminal prosecution may be sought by management and/or the audit team;
In the case of the deceased or those who have been separated from service, make representations with the proper prosecuting agencies of the government towards the institution of the necessary proceedings for the recovery of the amount of the cash advance as provided in Section 4.1 of COA Circular No. 86-256; and
File a request for authority to write-off for the accounts that are deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, to be guided by the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-08 dated August 17, 2023.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the HRMO to immediately update in the GSIS portal the salary details of employees;
Advice the municipal accountant and HRMO to confer with GSIS on the reconciliation of unpaid premiums per individual accounts;
Confer with the GSIS management and the LGU employees on the best resolution for the unpaid premiums

We recommended that management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Update the individual records of properties and submit to the Office of the Auditor an aging of the RPT and SET delinquencies as of December 31, 2023;
Comply with the posting requirements necessary for the collection of delinquencies;
Conduct extensive tax campaigns in all of the barangays so that taxpayers are apprised of their rights and obligations incidental to their ownership of properties including consequences for non-payment of RPT/SET.
Submit to the accountant by year-end the List of RPT and SET delinquencies that can no longer be collected, as the basis for recognizing impairment loss;
Likewise, we recommend that management:
Spearhead digitalizing the RPT and SET records management in CY 2024 by preparing adequate budgetary support in this regard, and enjoining the Sangguniang Bayan for its approval;
Initiate availing of the administrative and/or judicial remedies for delinquencies within the prescriptive period.

We recommended that management:
Direct the municipal assessor to prepare a financial and operational plan and requirements to carry out the tax mapping;
Enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to support funding initiatives for the preparation of tax maps and subsequent related activities thereto.

We recommended that management:
Incorporate in its prospective contract agreements a provision requiring the submission of SWA as of year-end;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with the said SWA as the basis for her accrual of liabilities;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record accrual of liabilities on works accomplished as of year-end.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the municipal accountant to reconcile and adjust the Due to LGU account by communicating with other LGU accountants to which the municipality has an obligation to;
Prioritize earmarking of cash back-up for Inter-Agency Payables;
Enjoin the Sangguniang Bayan to appropriate from the General Fund residual cash insufficiencies in the Trust Fund.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the municipal treasurer and the accountant to communicate to the Source Agencies (SAs) a written request for a copy of the MOA for the subject fund transfers;
Initiate the preparation of MOA between the NGAs, if such were not constituted on the subject fund transfers tied with specific purposes;
Direct the municipal engineer to coordinate and furnish the municipal accountant with the completion certificates and/or project status for those without readily available information;
Execute prompt implementation of projects funded by the NGAs;
Enjoin the focal person of each project to submit status reports and other relevant documents to assist in the liquidation of funds; and
Return to the SAs any unused funds of the completed projects as prescribed under COA Circular No. 94-013.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that management:
Require the municipal engineer to prepare the Program of Works (POW) on infrastructure programs, prior to the approval of the 20% DF or in the 1st quarter of the budget year, to improve implementation efficiency;
Revisit its planning process, anticipating the current and future needs, to avoid reprioritization and further delays in implementing development-driven PPAs.

We recommended that management:
Revise the existing contingency plans to incorporate mitigating measures in the anatomy of hazards;
Instruct the LDRRMO to fast-track the preparation of a contingency plan for flooding;
Enjoin the LDRRM Council to provide fund linkage between the mitigating measures and gaps identified in the contingency plan, to maximize the disaster preparedness of the local government

We recommended that management:
Direct all department heads to coordinate and aid the GFPS in providing the lacking information to generate a well-equipped GAD database;
Require the GFPS to issue a compliance certificate that the concerned department heads/ participants have coordinated and supplied the lacking data for a well-equipped GAD database prior to their attendance to a GAD planning session.

We recommended that the:
a. MDRRM Council, thru the MDRRM Officer, provide justification on the charging of the procurement of antigen test kits and face mask in the 30% QRF despite indicating said items under disaster preparedness in the LDRRMFSIP;
b. Municipal Budget Officer provide justification on the noted observation relative the budgeting of the Municipal Government. Henceforth, ensure that the budget for the ensuing years is prepared in accordance with the procedures/schedules and local budget preparation forms prescribed under the Budget Operations Manual for LGUs;
c. Local Health Board submit justification on the observation regarding the two separate versions of Resolution No. 1, series of 2020;
d. Municipal Health Officer submit proof of compliance with the provision of Item 6.4 of DBM-DOH JC No. 1 and JC No. 2, s. 2020 and the data relative the number of COVID-19 vaccines received and number of individuals inoculated in CY 2021;
e. Municipal Accountant submit the support to the claim for AHDP totaling ₱31,363.63 of the four Barangay Health Workers, otherwise, cause the refund of the said amount;
f. BAC Secretariat observe the proper form of the purchase order and accomplish it thoroughly, and see to it that the date of acceptance by the supplier is indicated in the PO in compliance with COA Circular No. 96-010 and the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
g. Municipal Treasurer require the supplier to issue either a Sales Invoice (for goods) or Official Receipt (for goods/services) for every payment made by the Municipal Government, and ensure that disbursement vouchers and supporting documents be stamped “paid” after the payee claimed the check; and
h. MDRRM Officer and MSWD Officer submit the distribution list of the welfare goods and face mask distributed in CY 2021.

We recommended that the:
a. Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and BAC Secretariat provide acceptable justification on the noted procedural lapses such as acceptance of Bid Securing Declaration and Omnibus Sworn Statement not in the prescribed format, non-submission of Statement of Single Largest Completed Contract and non-attachment of Owner’s Certificate of Final Acceptance or Constructors Performance Evaluation System, non-compliance with the 6th edition of the Philippine Bidding Documents, among others in the procurement funded by the National Government. Henceforth, ensure strict compliance with the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and of related GPPB issuances in the procurement of the Municipal Government;
b. Municipal Accountant ensure compliance with the provision of Letter of Instruction (LOI) 968 dated December 17, 1979 and the submission of the Certificate of Availability of Funds pursuant to Section 86 of PD No. 1445;
c. Municipal Engineer provide justification on the noted observations in the implementation of the project such as the conduct of Flexural/Compressive Test for the Concreting of FMR at Sitio Macasaet, San Gabriel prior to the opening of bids, issuance of the suspension order and extension of contract time, inconsistencies in the dates of the approved Construction Safety and Health Program, undated program of works, non-compliance with DILG MCs No. 2019-71 dated May 20, 2019 and 2020-088 dated May 21, 2020, among others. Henceforth, ensure compliance with the provision of Section 2.23 of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 relative to the posting of billboards, and Annexes A and E of the IRR of RA No. 9184 and various issuances of the National Government relative the funds received in the preparation of detailed engineering and implementation of infrastructure projects;
d. Municipal Accountant, Municipal Engineer and BAC Chairperson submit justification on the noted observation in the procurement and implementation of the projects, and submit all the lacking documents for audit purposes in compliance with Section 4(6) of PD 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and pertinent provisions of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
e. BAC Chairperson instruct the BAC Secretariat to use the 6th edition of the Philippine Bidding Documents as provided in GPPB Circular No. 04-2020 dated September 16, 2020 and GPPB Resolution No. 16-2020 dated September 16, 2020; and
f. Municipal Treasurer ensure that disbursement vouchers and supporting documents be stamped “paid” after the payee claimed the check.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:

a. the Municipal Accountant to record all purchases of supplies and materials as inventory items and not directly charged as expense and to record those items issued/consumed as expenses only during the accounting period;

b. direct the MGSO to:
   b.1 properly maintain and observe the updated Stock Cards for each inventory item;
   b.2 record all receipts and issuances of supplies in the stock cards;
   b.3 prepare and consolidate all Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for which supplies and materials were issued using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) with complete details and submit the same to the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO);
   b.4 reconcile the Stock Cards periodically with the ledger cards of the MAO; and
   b.5 conduct physical count of inventories semestrally, generate/prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year.

c. require the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to:
   c.1 reconcile the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories with the GL controlling accounts; and
   c.2 draw a Journal Entry Voucher to record the adjustments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:

b. Municipal Accountant to reconcile the ledger balance of the CIP accounts with the Quarterly Report on Government PPAs submitted by the Engineering Office and record the necessary adjustments, if any, pursuant to Paragraph 4, Section 50 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

a. Municipal Engineer to submit to COA the Quarterly Reports on Government PPAs with complete and correct details such as target completion date, percentage of completion, total cost incurred to date and project status, copy furnish the Municipal Accountant as basis for recording/adjustment in the books of the completed projects to its appropriate account;

a. Municipal Budget Officer to prepare the Annual Operating Budget for each Local Economic Enterprise as required by the Budget Operations Manual for LGUs;

b. MSWMB to review and update the Ten-Year Solid Waste Management Plan of the Municipality and subsequently, every two years or as the need arises, in compliance with Section 4 (g), Rule VI of the IRR of RA No. 9003;

c. MPDC to revisit the project feasibility study on the operation of the MRF to re-establish its medium-term and long-term viability and formulate and recommend fiscal plans and policies for its improvement pursuant to Section 476 (6) of RA No. 7160; and

d. Municipal Accountant to prepare a realistic/definite Statement of Financial Statements for MRF as required under the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume 1, to properly determine the financial status of the MRF.

a. MSDO to submit written justifications on the noted deficiencies in the implementation of the Social Amelioration Program of the DSWD and submit all necessary documents as required by Memorandum Circulars of the DSWD to support the receipt of the subsidy and the qualification of the beneficiaries;

b. Municipal Treasurer to submit the Official Receipts as proof of the return of cash assistance, otherwise, submit written explanations relative thereto; and

c. Municipal Accountant to submit records and/or Journal Entry Voucher relative to the refund of cash assistance.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the concerned Municipal officers to (i) prepare the necessary LDRRMFIP in accordance with the prescribed format inclusive of PPAs charged to unexpended LDRRMF of prior years; (ii) adhere to the applicable guidelines in the timely submission and complete reporting of donations during quarantine; and (iii) strictly comply with the abovementioned regulations with regards to the LDRRMF.

